INSERT INTO `wp_options` (`option_id`, `option_name`, `option_value`, `autoload`) VALUES(3874, '_transient_rss_0e98340d518ceed28b29f102e202ba76', 'O:9:"MagpieRSS":19:{s:6:"parser";i:0;s:12:"current_item";a:0:{}s:5:"items";a:10:{i:0;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:38:"AltoRouter, another PHP Routing class.";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/sBdvjk3Uwmk/";s:8:"comments";s:68:"http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 31 Jul 2012 19:07:20 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:24:"WebdevelopmentPHPRouting";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=745";s:11:"description";s:485:"<p>A few months earlier I blogged about developing PHP Router, a PHP5.3+ routing class with support for REST routing and reversed routing. Well, last week I came across klein.php, a lightweight PHP router developed by Chris O&#8217;Hara. I particularly liked the fact that it&#8217;s pretty easy to specify certain type restrictions for your URL parameters [...]</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/">AltoRouter, another PHP Routing class.</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:1519:"<p>A few months earlier I blogged about developing <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/" title="PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing">PHP Router</a>, a PHP5.3+ routing class with support for REST routing and reversed routing. </p>\n<p>Well, last week I came across <a href="http://github.com/chriso/klein.php/">klein.php</a>, a lightweight PHP router developed by Chris O&#8217;Hara. I particularly liked the fact that it&#8217;s pretty easy to specify certain type restrictions for your URL parameters so I decided to create my own version of klein.php. The aim was to create something that worked in a similar way as my own PHP Router class, but with the easiness of klein.php. </p>\n<p>So, here it is: <a href="http://github.com/dannyvankooten/AltoRouter">AltoRouter</a>, a tiny routing class which will help you in your future PHP projects.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Usage of different HTTP Methods</li>\n<li>Dynamic routing, which lets you capture certain uri segments as parameters</li>\n<li>REST Routing</li>\n<li>Reversed routing, generate URL&#8217;s from route names while supplying parameter values</li>\n<li>Wildcards</li>\n<li>Parameter types</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Have a look at the code. Tell me what you like / don&#8217;t like so we can improve AltoRouter together!</p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/">AltoRouter, another PHP Routing class.</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/sBdvjk3Uwmk" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:64:"http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"1";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:59:"http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/";}s:7:"summary";s:485:"<p>A few months earlier I blogged about developing PHP Router, a PHP5.3+ routing class with support for REST routing and reversed routing. Well, last week I came across klein.php, a lightweight PHP router developed by Chris O&#8217;Hara. I particularly liked the fact that it&#8217;s pretty easy to specify certain type restrictions for your URL parameters [...]</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/">AltoRouter, another PHP Routing class.</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:1519:"<p>A few months earlier I blogged about developing <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/" title="PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing">PHP Router</a>, a PHP5.3+ routing class with support for REST routing and reversed routing. </p>\n<p>Well, last week I came across <a href="http://github.com/chriso/klein.php/">klein.php</a>, a lightweight PHP router developed by Chris O&#8217;Hara. I particularly liked the fact that it&#8217;s pretty easy to specify certain type restrictions for your URL parameters so I decided to create my own version of klein.php. The aim was to create something that worked in a similar way as my own PHP Router class, but with the easiness of klein.php. </p>\n<p>So, here it is: <a href="http://github.com/dannyvankooten/AltoRouter">AltoRouter</a>, a tiny routing class which will help you in your future PHP projects.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Usage of different HTTP Methods</li>\n<li>Dynamic routing, which lets you capture certain uri segments as parameters</li>\n<li>REST Routing</li>\n<li>Reversed routing, generate URL&#8217;s from route names while supplying parameter values</li>\n<li>Wildcards</li>\n<li>Parameter types</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Have a look at the code. Tell me what you like / don&#8217;t like so we can improve AltoRouter together!</p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/">AltoRouter, another PHP Routing class.</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/sBdvjk3Uwmk" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:1;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:45:"PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/Z-fQJCu618A/";s:8:"comments";s:74:"http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 30 Nov 2011 22:04:10 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:34:"WebdevelopmentFrameworksPHPRouting";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=718";s:11:"description";s:481:"<p>In the last few months I&#8217;ve been looking into all the different PHP frameworks and how they glue things together. One of the most important things in every framework is the way it handles routes. I&#8217;ve been developing Ruby on Rails applications extensively last year and I really like the way Rails handles it&#8217;s routes. [...]</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/">PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3533:"<p>In the last few months I&#8217;ve been looking into all the different PHP frameworks and how they glue things together. One of the most important things in every framework is the way it handles routes. I&#8217;ve been developing Ruby on Rails applications extensively last year and I really like the way Rails handles it&#8217;s routes. That&#8217;s why I&#8217;ve decided to start programming a Routing class that mimics Rails routing functionality.</p>\n<p>I&#8217;ve released this PHP Routing class on Github <a href="https://github.com/dannyvankooten/PHP-Router">here</a>, so you can follow and contribute to it&#8217;s development progress.</p>\n<h4>What does this PHP Routing class do?</h4>\n<p>In short, this class helps you route URL&#8217;s to their corresponding Controller and action methods. You can use different HTTP methods to fully benefit from using REST / resourceful routes. Also, setting up dynamic URL&#8217;s that pass parameters to their corresponding action are no problem.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>REST Routing</li>\n<li>Use different HTTP methods for same URL&#8217;s</li>\n<li>Dynamic URL segments</li>\n<li>Reversed routing, create URL from route</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The class is fairly simple and lightweight, it won&#8217;t do any unnecessary processing. Have a look at the following snippet taken from the example file to get a better understanding on how to use this class in your projects.</p>\n<pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\nrequire ''Router.php'';\n\n$r = new Router();\n\n// maps / to controller ''users'' and method ''index''.\n$r-&gt;match(''/'',''users#index'');\n\n// maps /user/5 to controller ''users'', method ''show'' with parameter ''id'' =&gt; 5\n$r-&gt;match(''/user/:id'',''users#show'');\n\n// maps POST request to /users/ to controller ''users'' and method ''create''\n$r-&gt;match(''/users'',''users#create'',array(''via'' =&gt; ''post''));\n\n// maps GET /users/5/edit to controller ''users'', method ''edit'' with parameters ''id'' =&gt; 5 and saves route as a named route.\n$r-&gt;match(''/users/:id/edit'',''users#edit'',array(''via'' =&gt; ''get'', ''as'' =&gt; ''user_edit_page''));\n\n// echoes /users/5/edit\necho $r-&gt;reverse(''user_edit_page'',array(''id'' =&gt; ''5''));\n\n// maps multiple routes\n// GET /users will map to users#index\n// GET /users/5 will map to users#show\n$r-&gt;resources(''users'',array(''only'' =&gt; ''index,show''));\n\n\nif($r-&gt;hasRoute()) {\n    // extract controller, action and parameters.\n    extract($r-&gt;getRoute());\n\n    ?&gt;\n    &lt;h1&gt;Route found!&lt;/h1&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Controller: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php echo $controller; ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Action: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php echo $action; ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Params: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php var_dump($params); ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;?php\n\n} else {\n    ?&gt;&lt;h1&gt;No route found.&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;?php\n}\n\n?&gt;\n</pre>\n<p>If you&#8217;re using this class and experience any issues, please post them using GitHub&#8217;s issue tracker. Also, feel free to geek around and fork the project to improve this class. </p>\n<p><a href="https://github.com/dannyvankooten/PHP-Router">Watch PHP Routing Class on Github!</a></p>\n<p>UPDATE (31/07/2012): If you like PHP Router you might also like <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/" title="AltoRouter, another PHP Routing class.">AltoRouter</a>. </p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/">PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/Z-fQJCu618A" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:70:"http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"3";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:65:"http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/";}s:7:"summary";s:481:"<p>In the last few months I&#8217;ve been looking into all the different PHP frameworks and how they glue things together. One of the most important things in every framework is the way it handles routes. I&#8217;ve been developing Ruby on Rails applications extensively last year and I really like the way Rails handles it&#8217;s routes. [...]</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/">PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:3533:"<p>In the last few months I&#8217;ve been looking into all the different PHP frameworks and how they glue things together. One of the most important things in every framework is the way it handles routes. I&#8217;ve been developing Ruby on Rails applications extensively last year and I really like the way Rails handles it&#8217;s routes. That&#8217;s why I&#8217;ve decided to start programming a Routing class that mimics Rails routing functionality.</p>\n<p>I&#8217;ve released this PHP Routing class on Github <a href="https://github.com/dannyvankooten/PHP-Router">here</a>, so you can follow and contribute to it&#8217;s development progress.</p>\n<h4>What does this PHP Routing class do?</h4>\n<p>In short, this class helps you route URL&#8217;s to their corresponding Controller and action methods. You can use different HTTP methods to fully benefit from using REST / resourceful routes. Also, setting up dynamic URL&#8217;s that pass parameters to their corresponding action are no problem.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>REST Routing</li>\n<li>Use different HTTP methods for same URL&#8217;s</li>\n<li>Dynamic URL segments</li>\n<li>Reversed routing, create URL from route</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The class is fairly simple and lightweight, it won&#8217;t do any unnecessary processing. Have a look at the following snippet taken from the example file to get a better understanding on how to use this class in your projects.</p>\n<pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\nrequire ''Router.php'';\n\n$r = new Router();\n\n// maps / to controller ''users'' and method ''index''.\n$r-&gt;match(''/'',''users#index'');\n\n// maps /user/5 to controller ''users'', method ''show'' with parameter ''id'' =&gt; 5\n$r-&gt;match(''/user/:id'',''users#show'');\n\n// maps POST request to /users/ to controller ''users'' and method ''create''\n$r-&gt;match(''/users'',''users#create'',array(''via'' =&gt; ''post''));\n\n// maps GET /users/5/edit to controller ''users'', method ''edit'' with parameters ''id'' =&gt; 5 and saves route as a named route.\n$r-&gt;match(''/users/:id/edit'',''users#edit'',array(''via'' =&gt; ''get'', ''as'' =&gt; ''user_edit_page''));\n\n// echoes /users/5/edit\necho $r-&gt;reverse(''user_edit_page'',array(''id'' =&gt; ''5''));\n\n// maps multiple routes\n// GET /users will map to users#index\n// GET /users/5 will map to users#show\n$r-&gt;resources(''users'',array(''only'' =&gt; ''index,show''));\n\n\nif($r-&gt;hasRoute()) {\n    // extract controller, action and parameters.\n    extract($r-&gt;getRoute());\n\n    ?&gt;\n    &lt;h1&gt;Route found!&lt;/h1&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Controller: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php echo $controller; ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Action: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php echo $action; ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Params: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php var_dump($params); ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;?php\n\n} else {\n    ?&gt;&lt;h1&gt;No route found.&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;?php\n}\n\n?&gt;\n</pre>\n<p>If you&#8217;re using this class and experience any issues, please post them using GitHub&#8217;s issue tracker. Also, feel free to geek around and fork the project to improve this class. </p>\n<p><a href="https://github.com/dannyvankooten/PHP-Router">Watch PHP Routing Class on Github!</a></p>\n<p>UPDATE (31/07/2012): If you like PHP Router you might also like <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/745/altorouter-php-routing-class/" title="AltoRouter, another PHP Routing class.">AltoRouter</a>. </p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/">PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/Z-fQJCu618A" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:2;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:64:"Newsletter Sign-Up, added configuration helper: Config Extractor";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/JaHzuDw9hVg/";s:8:"comments";s:102:"http://dannyvankooten.com/703/newsletter-sign-up-added-configuration-helper-config-extractor/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 12 Nov 2011 12:00:06 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:27:"WordPressnewsletter-sign-up";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=703";s:11:"description";s:534:"<p>With Newsletter Sign-Up having been downloaded over 50.000 times (combined with the old plugin) it was about time for me to release another update. I&#8217;ve been getting more and more e-mails on how to properly configure the plugin so I decided that&#8217;s where the plugin could use some improvements. Although my detailed post on how to [...]</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/703/newsletter-sign-up-added-configuration-helper-config-extractor/">Newsletter Sign-Up, added configuration helper: Config Extractor</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:2966:"<p>With Newsletter Sign-Up having been downloaded over 50.000 times (combined with the old plugin) it was about time for me to release another update. I&#8217;ve been getting more and more e-mails on <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/571/configuring-newsletter-sign-up-the-definitive-guide/">how to properly configure the plugin</a> so I decided that&#8217;s where the plugin could use some improvements.</p>\n<p>Although my detailed post on how to configure it certainly helped I decided it would be cool if I built some kind of tool that helped new users extract the right configuration settings for them. So here it is, the &#8220;configuration extractor&#8221; that comes with version 1.5.0 of Newsletter Sign-Up.</p>\n<h2>How does this &#8220;configuration extractor&#8221; work?</h2>\n<p>Basically all you have to do is provide a form snippet that you would normally embed in your website&#8217;s HTML code, paste it in the configuration extractor text area and hit the extract button. The tool will then try to extract the different values which are needed to get <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wordpress-plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">Newsletter Sign-up</a> to work. The tool is still pretty minimal but I will work on it to improve it during the next weeks.</p>\n<p>When the configuration settings the tool provided did not work, you can now more easily extract the right values yourself by using the cleaned up form that comes with the results of the configuration extractor. This is basically a stripped down version of your Sign-up form, which makes it way easier to extract the correct settings.</p>\n<p>Have a look at the following screenshots to get a better idea of how the tool works or download <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wordpress-plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">Newsletter Sign-Up v1.5</a> straight away!</p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/config-extractor-input.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-704" title="config-extractor-input" src="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/config-extractor-input.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="506" /></a><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/config-extractor-results.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-705" title="config-extractor-results" src="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/config-extractor-results.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="455" /></a></p>\n<p>Let me know what you think of this update. The next thing i&#8217;ll work on is error handling and providing an easier alternative to style the form, besides using plain CSS. Of course all suggestions on how to improve Newsletter Sign-Up are welcome !</p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/703/newsletter-sign-up-added-configuration-helper-config-extractor/">Newsletter Sign-Up, added configuration helper: Config Extractor</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/JaHzuDw9hVg" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:98:"http://dannyvankooten.com/703/newsletter-sign-up-added-configuration-helper-config-extractor/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:93:"http://dannyvankooten.com/703/newsletter-sign-up-added-configuration-helper-config-extractor/";}s:7:"summary";s:534:"<p>With Newsletter Sign-Up having been downloaded over 50.000 times (combined with the old plugin) it was about time for me to release another update. I&#8217;ve been getting more and more e-mails on how to properly configure the plugin so I decided that&#8217;s where the plugin could use some improvements. Although my detailed post on how to [...]</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/703/newsletter-sign-up-added-configuration-helper-config-extractor/">Newsletter Sign-Up, added configuration helper: Config Extractor</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:2966:"<p>With Newsletter Sign-Up having been downloaded over 50.000 times (combined with the old plugin) it was about time for me to release another update. I&#8217;ve been getting more and more e-mails on <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/571/configuring-newsletter-sign-up-the-definitive-guide/">how to properly configure the plugin</a> so I decided that&#8217;s where the plugin could use some improvements.</p>\n<p>Although my detailed post on how to configure it certainly helped I decided it would be cool if I built some kind of tool that helped new users extract the right configuration settings for them. So here it is, the &#8220;configuration extractor&#8221; that comes with version 1.5.0 of Newsletter Sign-Up.</p>\n<h2>How does this &#8220;configuration extractor&#8221; work?</h2>\n<p>Basically all you have to do is provide a form snippet that you would normally embed in your website&#8217;s HTML code, paste it in the configuration extractor text area and hit the extract button. The tool will then try to extract the different values which are needed to get <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wordpress-plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">Newsletter Sign-up</a> to work. The tool is still pretty minimal but I will work on it to improve it during the next weeks.</p>\n<p>When the configuration settings the tool provided did not work, you can now more easily extract the right values yourself by using the cleaned up form that comes with the results of the configuration extractor. This is basically a stripped down version of your Sign-up form, which makes it way easier to extract the correct settings.</p>\n<p>Have a look at the following screenshots to get a better idea of how the tool works or download <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wordpress-plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">Newsletter Sign-Up v1.5</a> straight away!</p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/config-extractor-input.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-704" title="config-extractor-input" src="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/config-extractor-input.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="506" /></a><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/config-extractor-results.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-705" title="config-extractor-results" src="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/config-extractor-results.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="455" /></a></p>\n<p>Let me know what you think of this update. The next thing i&#8217;ll work on is error handling and providing an easier alternative to style the form, besides using plain CSS. Of course all suggestions on how to improve Newsletter Sign-Up are welcome !</p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/703/newsletter-sign-up-added-configuration-helper-config-extractor/